equals

public static boolean equals(java.lang.Object a,
                             java.lang.Object b)
Compares 2 objects Object.equals(java.lang.Object). Classes should be annotated using @JAUEquals (directly or through the corresponding package) to be compared using reflection. Static and synthetic fields will be ignored.

Parameters:
a - first object or null
b - second object or null
Returns:

true, if (a == null) && (b == null)

false, if (a == null) && (b != null)

false, if (a != null) && (b == null)

true, if (a == b)

false, if (a.getClass() != b.getClass())

arrays are compared deeply using this method for each element for classes annotated with JAUEquals only fields annotated with EqualsProperty will be taken into account and compared

If a class is not annotated, but implements java.util.Map, it is compared so JAU.equals() is called for each value instead of a.equals(b)

a.equals(b) otherwise

clone

public static java.lang.Object clone(java.lang.Object a)
Firstly, this method creates an object: either by - invoking clone if the class of a implements Cloneable - invoking the default constructor (even if it is private) - invoking the copy constructor if it exists (in this case there will be no special field copying) Copies of the following classes are not created: String.class Byte.class Short.class Integer.class Long.class Float.class Double.class Class.class Object.class BigDecimal.class BigInteger.class

a - an object or null
Returns:
null, if a == null copy of a otherwise

compare

public static int compare(java.lang.Object a,
                          java.lang.Object b)
                   throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
Compares 2 objects Object.equals(java.lang.Object). Classes should be annotated using JAUCompareTo (directly or through the corresponding package) to be compared using reflection. Otherwise if a class implements Comparable it's compareTo method is used. Fields in a class are compared from to top bottom (e.g. first field is more important for comparison than the second one). Fields from superclass are more important and will be compared first. Static and synthetic fields will be ignored.

Parameters:
a - first object or null
b - second object or null
Returns:
< 0, if a < b > 0, if a > b 0, if a = b Special cases: 0, if (a == null) && (b == null) -1, if (a == null) && (b != null) 1, if (a != null) && (b == null) 0, if (a == b) arrays are compared deeply using this method for each element for classes annotated with JAUCompareTo only fields annotated with JAUCompareTo will be taken into account and compared a.compareTo(b) otherwise
Throws:
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if a.getClass() != b.getClass() or the class is not annotated and does not implement Comparable

toMap

public static java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.Object> toMap(java.lang.Object a)
Creates a map filled with properties from an object. Classes should be annotated using JAUToMap (directly or through the corresponding package) for this to work. Static and synthetic fields will be ignored.

Parameters:
an - object or null
Returns:
a map filled with the property values from a. An empty map is returned if a is null. Otherwise there will be an entry for every property from a with the value from the object. The returned map is mutable. An empty map is returned if a is an array or the class of a is not annotated.

fromMap

public static void fromMap(java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.Object> map,
                           java.lang.Object a)
Fills an object with properties stored in a map. Classes should be annotated using JAUToMap (directly or through the corresponding package) for this to work. Static and synthetic fields will be ignored.

Parameters:
an - object or null
map - a map filled with the property values, which will be stored in a. Nothing is done if a is null or the class of a is not annotated or an array. Otherwise properties stored in a.
